{"type":"message","id":"162fa4a8","parentId":"492b7c0b","timestamp":"2026-03-03T14:51:35.843Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is asking about ensuring tasks are being written and picked up. They want to make sure there's a task queue system that actually works - tasks get written (by some trigger) and then picked up (by the appropriate agent).\n\nCurrently:\n1. The `temujin/tasks/` directory exists but is empty\n2. The heartbeat daemon was supposed to have a context_review task that creates tasks, but that task isn't registered\n3. The proactive spawning protocol allows agents to spawn sub-agents directly, which is one way to handle tasks\n\nSo the question is: do we need a file-based task queue (tasks written to temujin/tasks/), or is the sessions_spawn approach sufficient?\n\nI should clarify with the user what they want - do they want:\n1. A file-based task queue where tasks are written to directories and picked up\n2. Or is the direct sessions_spawn approach sufficient\n\nGiven the context of \"ensure tasks are being written and picked up\", I think they want a system where:\n1. Tasks get created (written) automatically when there's work to do\n2. Agents pick up and execute those tasks\n\nLet me ask for clarification on which approach they prefer, or I could implement both:\n1. The file-based task queue (as documented in ARCHITECTURE.md)\n2. Direct spawning via sessions_spawn\n\nLet me implement the file-based task queue system since that's what they're asking about.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"Good point. The task queue system isn't fully implemented. Currently:\n\n- **`temujin/tasks/`** directory exists but is **empty**\n- No system writes tasks there\n- No system picks them up\n\nTwo approaches available:\n\n1. **File-based queue** (as documented in ARCHITECTURE.md): Tasks written to `temujin/tasks/*.md`, picked up by agent\n2. **Direct spawning** (just implemented): Agent spawns sub-agent directly via `sessions_spawn`\n\nThe ARCHITECTURE.md mentions a `kublai/context_review` task that should detect code needs and create task files — but it's not in the codebase.\n\n**Recommend:** Implement the file-based task queue system so:\n1. Tasks get written to `agent/temujin/tasks/` (or respective agent)\n2. A consumer script picks them up and executes\n\nWant me to implement this now? It would add:\n- Task writer (what triggers writing?)\n- Task consumer (polls directory, executes)\n- Agent-specific task directories (temujin/tasks/, mongke/tasks/, etc.)"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"bailian","model":"MiniMax-M2.5","usage":{"input":1034,"output":812,"cacheRead":57854,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":59700,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1772549479051}}
