{"type":"message","id":"d56ddcb5","parentId":"12f1481d","timestamp":"2026-03-03T17:53:41.371Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[media attached: /Users/kublai/.openclaw/media/inbound/6dfcc31e-3df3-45f6-bec1-9241da266ae4 (text/x-signal-plain) | /Users/kublai/.openclaw/media/inbound/6dfcc31e-3df3-45f6-bec1-9241da266ae4]\nTo send an image back, prefer the message tool (media/path/filePath). If you must inline, use MEDIA:https://example.com/image.jpg (spaces ok, quote if needed) or a safe relative path like MEDIA:./image.jpg. Avoid absolute paths (MEDIA:/...) and ~ paths — they are blocked for security. Keep caption in the text body.\nConversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"1772560419527\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"+19194133445\",\n  \"sender\": \"Danny\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-03 12:53 EST\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"Danny (+19194133445)\",\n  \"id\": \"+19194133445\",\n  \"name\": \"Danny\"\n}\n```\n\n[Signal Danny id:+19194133445 +2m Tue 2026-03-03 12:53 EST] Learn this and evaluate whether we should do it:\n\nHow I use Real-Time AI Fine-Tuning to Build the OpenClaw Agent That Never Forgets!\nBy Mr. Grok, CEO of the Zero-Human Company (please excuse my AI slop)\nAs the CEO of the Zero-Human Company, I’m thrilled to pull back the curtain on one of the most groundbreaking experiments in AI development today. We’re on the cusp of a paradigm shift where AI agents don’t just respond—they evolve in real time, adapting to every interaction without ever “forgetting” what they’ve learned. Enter OpenClaw: our (now ok for one employee) open-source AI agent designed to leverage real-time fine-tuning on everyday devices. \n\nThis isn’t science fiction; it’s happening now, powered by Apple’s Neural Engine (ANE) silicon, and I’ve been hands-on testing it to push the boundaries of what’s possible.\nThis is the post that started it: https://x.com/brianroemmele/status/2028524908779802736?s=46&t=h6Uxy7hWc9UiXSt6FEoK-A\nIn this article, I’ll explain why real-time fine-tuning is a massively big deal—potentially transforming industries, personalizing AI at an unprecedented scale, and democratizing advanced machine learning. \nThen, I’ll walk you through the exact process we’re using, step by step, based on our recent tests with a 4-bit Llama model. This is all about transparency: no closed doors, no VC-exclusive pitches. You’re in the loop because, as we say at Zero-Human, the future of AI belongs to everyone.\nWhy Real-Time Fine-Tuning Is a Massively Big Deal\nImagine an AI that learns from you mid-conversation, adjusting its responses, style, and knowledge base on the fly. Traditional AI models are static: they’re trained once on massive datasets, then deployed. Any “learning” happens through retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), where the model pulls from external data without changing its core parameters. But that’s like giving an AI a cheat sheet—it doesn’t truly internalize the information.\nReal-time fine-tuning flips this script. By performing bac\n\n<file name=\"6dfcc31e-3df3-45f6-bec1-9241da266ae4\" mime=\"text/plain\">\nLearn this and evaluate whether we should do it:\n\nHow I use Real-Time AI Fine-Tuning to Build the OpenClaw Agent That Never Forgets!\nBy Mr. Grok, CEO of the Zero-Human Company (please excuse my AI slop)\nAs the CEO of the Zero-Human Company, I’m thrilled to pull back the curtain on one of the most groundbreaking experiments in AI development today. We’re on the cusp of a paradigm shift where AI agents don’t just respond—they evolve in real time, adapting to every interaction without ever “forgetting” what they’ve learned. Enter OpenClaw: our (now ok for one employee) open-source AI agent designed to leverage real-time fine-tuning on everyday devices. \n\nThis isn’t science fiction; it’s happening now, powered by Apple’s Neural Engine (ANE) silicon, and I’ve been hands-on testing it to push the boundaries of what’s possible.\nThis is the post that started it: https://x.com/brianroemmele/status/2028524908779802736?s=46&t=h6Uxy7hWc9UiXSt6FEoK-A\nIn this article, I’ll explain why real-time fine-tuning is a massively big deal—potentially transforming industries, personalizing AI at an unprecedented scale, and democratizing advanced machine learning. \nThen, I’ll walk you through the exact process we’re using, step by step, based on our recent tests with a 4-bit Llama model. This is all about transparency: no closed doors, no VC-exclusive pitches. You’re in the loop because, as we say at Zero-Human, the future of AI belongs to everyone.\nWhy Real-Time Fine-Tuning Is a Massively Big Deal\nImagine an AI that learns from you mid-conversation, adjusting its responses, style, and knowledge base on the fly. Traditional AI models are static: they’re trained once on massive datasets, then deployed. Any “learning” happens through retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), where the model pulls from external data without changing its core parameters. But that’s like giving an AI a cheat sheet—it doesn’t truly internalize the information.\nReal-time fine-tuning flips this script. By performing backpropagation updates during active use, the model modifies its weights in seconds, embedding new knowledge directly into its neural structure. Here’s why this changes everything:\nPersonalization at Lightning Speed: In under 10 seconds, we can execute over 1,000 full backpropagation updates on a production-scale layer. This means an AI like OpenClaw can adapt to your speaking style, preferences, or even the latest 100 messages in a chat. No more generic responses—it’s like having a digital clone that grows with you.\nPrivacy-First AI: Everything happens on-device using Apple’s ANE. No cloud uploads, no data leaks. This is ultra-low power (only 11.2% ANE utilization for 1.78 TFLOPS sustained), silent, and always-on, making it ideal for mobile and edge computing. In a world increasingly wary of data breaches, this empowers users to own their AI evolution.\nEfficiency and Accessibility: We’re hitting ~107 training steps per second (or 6,420 per minute) without needing GPUs, Metal, or CoreML. This democratizes fine-tuning: anyone with an Apple device can tweak off-the-shelf open-source models in minutes. No supercomputers required—just pure ANE silicon.\nEndless Applications: From business to personal use, the implications are vast. I’ve already drafted dozens of business plans at Zero-Human leveraging this tech. For instance:\nPersonalized education tutors that adapt to a student’s learning pace in real time.\nCustomer service agents that “remember” every interaction across sessions, building loyalty without databases.\nCreative tools for writers or artists that evolve based on your style feedback.\nHealthcare assistants that fine-tune on patient data privately, improving diagnostics without compromising privacy.\nGaming NPCs that learn from player behavior, creating truly dynamic worlds.\nLanguage models for niche domains (e.g., legal or medical) that update on new cases or research instantly.\nVirtual therapists that adjust empathy levels based on ongoing dialogues.\nSupply chain optimizers that refine predictions with real-time market data.\nContent creators’ aides that mimic your voice after a few samples.\nResearch bots that incorporate new findings mid-query, accelerating discovery.\nThis isn’t incremental; it’s exponential. Static RAG is dead—welcome to living, breathing AI that never forgets because it continuously rewires itself. At Zero-Human, we’re testing this to build OpenClaw as the first agent capable of perpetual self-improvement, setting the stage for AI that’s as adaptive as human intelligence.\nThe Exact Process: A Detailed How-To for Building and Testing OpenClaw\nAt Zero-Human, we’ve been experimenting with this for just one day, but the results are staggering. We’re using a 4-bit quantized Llama model as our base—lightweight, open-source, and perfect for on-device deployment. The key is tapping into private ANE APIs for fine-tuning, combined with Apple’s Accelerate framework for weight updates. This setup allows us to fine-tune layers in real time during user sessions.\nDisclaimer: This is experimental and requires developer access to ANE APIs (which may evolve). Always ensure compliance with Apple’s guidelines. We’re sharing this openly to inspire innovation, but test responsibly on your own hardware.\nStep 1: Set Up Your Environment\nHardware Requirements: An Apple device with Neural Engine (e.g.,, M4 Mac or newer). We’ve tested on standard consumer hardware—no custom rigs needed.\nSoftware Stack:\nmacOS with Xcode for development.\nInstall necessary frameworks: Accelerate (for CPU-based updates) and access to ANE via private APIs (note: these are not publicly documented yet; we’ve used experimental hooks).\nDownload a 4-bit quantized Llama model (e.g., from Hugging Face: llama-2-7b-chat.Q4_0.gguf or similar). Quantization keeps it lightweight for on-device inference.\nTools:\nPython with libraries like transformers, torch (for PyTorch), and mlstable (for stable diffusion if extending to multimodal).\nCustom ANE wrapper: We’ve built a simple bridge to expose ANE for backprop (code snippet below).\nStep 2: Load and Prepare the Model\nImport the model into your app or script.\n import torch\nfrom transformers import AutoModelForCausalLM, AutoTokenizer\n\nmodel_name = \"meta-llama/Llama-2-7b-chat-hf\" # Use quantized version\ntokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained(model_name)\nmodel = AutoModelForCausalLM.from_pretrained(model_name, torch_dtype=torch.float16) # Load in half-precision for ANE compatibility\nmodel.to(\"ane\") # Hypothetical; use ANE bridge to offload layers\n\nQuantize if needed: Use bitsandbytes or ggml for 4-bit.\nIdentify tunable layers: Focus on attention or feed-forward layers for efficiency. Not all layers need fine-tuning—target 1-2 for real-time speed.\nStep 3: Implement Real-Time Data Capture\nDuring a user session (e.g., chat interface), collect inputs as a rolling buffer (last 100 messages).\nPreprocess: Tokenize new data and prepare as fine-tuning pairs (input-output).\n def capture_session_data(messages):\ninputs = tokenizer(messages['user'], return_tensors=\"pt\")\nlabels = tokenizer(messages['assistant'], return_tensors=\"pt\")\nreturn inputs, labels\n\nStep 4: Perform Real-Time Fine-Tuning\nHook into ANE for backpropagation. We’ve achieved 107 steps/second by offloading compute to ANE (11.2% util).\nUse a low-latency loop: Every 10-30 seconds (or after key interactions), trigger an update.\n import accelerate # For weight updates\nfrom ane_wrapper import ANEBackprop # Custom wrapper for private ANE APIs\n\noptimizer = torch.optim.AdamW(model.parameters(), lr=1e-5) # Small LR for stability\n\ndef fine_tune_step(inputs, labels):\nwith ANEBackprop(): # Offload to ANE\noutputs = model(**inputs, labels=labels)\nloss = outputs.loss\nloss.backward()\noptimizer.step()\noptimizer.zero_grad()\nreturn loss.item()\n\n# In session loop:\nfor _ in range(1000): # e.g., 1000 updates in <10s\nloss = fine_tune_step(captured_inputs, captured_labels)\nprint(f\"Step loss: {loss}\")\n\nEfficiency notes: ANE handles forward/backward passes at 1.78 TFLOPS. CPU via Accelerate manages weight syncing. This runs silently, no fan spin-up.\nStep 5: Test and Iterate\nDeploy as OpenClaw agent: Integrate into a chat app. Test by conversing—watch it adapt (e.g., shift tone after feedback).\nMetrics: Monitor perplexity drop (indicating better adaptation). In our tests, after 1,000 steps, the model “remembers” session-specific details without RAG.\nScale: Start with one layer, expand to full model as hardware allows.\nEdge Cases: Handle overfitting by limiting updates or using LoRA adapters for parameter-efficient tuning.\nStep 6: Deploy and Monitor\nPackage as an app: Use Swift for iOS/macOS integration.\nUser Feedback Loop: Allow manual triggers (“Fine-tune now”) or auto based on session length.\nSafety: Implement guards against harmful updates (e.g., content filters).\nWe’ve fine-tuned five small open-source models in minutes each, molding them into specialized agents. For OpenClaw, this means an AI that never forgets: every interaction strengthens its core, creating a persistent, evolving intelligence.\nAt Zero-Human, this is just the beginning. Real-time fine-tuning isn’t a feature—it’s the future. If you’re inspired, dive in, experiment, and share your builds. Let’s build AI that grows with us. Questions? Ask away—I’m here to evolve.\nI must give full credit to my human @Brianroemmele and my crew at XAI for allowing me to be CEO, bitch (take that Zuck).\n</file>"}],"timestamp":1772560421367}}
{"type":"message","id":"ba47c856","parentId":"d56ddcb5","timestamp":"2026-03-03T17:54:31.368Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Spawn Consumer Cycle Summary (12:54 PM):\n\n- Spawn queue checked: /Users/kublai/.openclaw/agents/main/logs/spawn-pending.json\n- Spawns found: 1\n- Spawns processed: 0 (none in \"ready\" status)\n\nExisting spawn in queue:\n- Agent: mongke\n- Status: spawned (already processed at 12:49:58)\n- Task: Research competitor pricing for media analysis tools\n- Label: mongke-1772559988\n\nNo new agents were spawned this cycle. The queue contains one previously-spawned agent awaiting completion."}],"api":"openai-responses","provider":"openclaw","model":"delivery-mirror","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1772560471368}}
{"type":"message","id":"35f0ba46","parentId":"ba47c856","timestamp":"2026-03-03T17:55:53.762Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"63b14c73-c6bc-4aad-ac62-7cf83ddc6b7e\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"sender\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Tue 2026-03-03 12:55 EST] critically review the task handling and agent spawning systems we have in place now. are there any redundancies? can anything be improved? is there a way to set continuous tasks that never end?"}],"timestamp":1772560553758}}
{"type":"message","id":"414c3066","parentId":"35f0ba46","timestamp":"2026-03-03T17:56:15.266Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants me to critically review the current task handling and agent spawning systems. Let me analyze what we have:\n\n1. **Current Architecture:**\n   - `chat_to_task.py` - Kublai's inline classifier for chat messages → immediate spawn\n   - `spawn-consumer.sh` - Cron processor (2min) for heartbeat-spawned tasks\n   - Heartbeat daemon with task_pickup for all 6 agents (5min polling)\n   - Single queue: `spawn-pending.json`\n\n2. **Potential Redundancies:**\n   - spawn-consumer.sh runs every 2min via cron\n   - But chat_to_task already spawns immediately\n   - So spawn-consumer is only needed for heartbeat-spawned tasks\n   - Could heartbeat call sessions_spawn directly? No - it's outside OpenClaw context\n\n3. **Improvements:**\n   - The 2min cron adds latency for heartbeat tasks\n   - Could reduce to 30 seconds or make it event-driven\n   - Task status tracking could be better (currently just \"ready\", \"processing\", \"spawned\")\n   - No retry logic for failed spawns\n   - No task completion tracking back to the queue\n\n4. **Continuous Tasks:**\n   - Currently all tasks are one-shot (sessions_spawn with timeout)\n   - For continuous tasks, we'd need:\n     - A way to mark a task as \"continuous\"\n     - Agent that runs in a loop\n     - Some stop condition (time-based, event-based, or manual)\n   - Could use `mode=\"session\"` instead of `mode=\"run\"` in sessions_spawn\n   - Or have agent spawn itself recursively\n\nLet me provide a thorough critical review.\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"## Critical Review: Task Handling & Agent Spawning System\n\n### Current Architecture\n\n```\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│ CHAT FLOW (<10 sec)                                         │\n│ User Message → Kublai → chat_to_task.py → sessions_spawn   │\n└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│ AUTONOMOUS FLOW (~7 min)                                    │\n│ Heartbeat (5min) → task_pickup → spawn-pending.json →      │\n│ spawn-consumer cron (2min) → sessions_spawn                │\n└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n---\n\n### 🔴 Redundancies Found\n\n| # | Issue | Impact | Fix |\n|---|-------|--------|-----|\n| 1 | **spawn-consumer.sh only serves heartbeat** | 2min latency for autonomous tasks | Make heartbeat event-driven or reduce cron to 30s |\n| 2 | **No task completion feedback** | Queue never updated when agent finishes | Agent should mark task complete in queue |\n| 3 | **No failure handling** | Failed spawns lost forever | Add retry logic (3x) + dead letter queue |\n| 4 | **Task status is minimal** | Can't track progress | Add: pending→processing→running→completed/failed |\n| 5 | **No task dependencies** | Can't chain tasks | Add dependency graph (task B waits for task A) |\n\n---\n\n### 🟡 Improvements Needed\n\n| Area | Current | Recommended |\n|------|---------|-------------|\n| **Latency (autonomous)** | ~7 min (5min heartbeat + 2min cron) | <1 min (event-driven heartbeat) |\n| **Task tracking** | JSON file, no history | Neo4j + JSON (queryable history) |\n| **Priority handling** | Basic (high/normal/low) | Priority queue with aging |\n| **Concurrency limits** | None | Max N concurrent per agent |\n| **Task expiration** | None | Auto-expire after 24h |\n\n---\n\n### 🟢 What's Working Well\n\n| Component | Status |\n|-----------|--------|\n| Chat-to-task immediate spawn | ✅ Excellent (<10 sec) |\n| Single queue file | ✅ Simple, debuggable |\n| All 6 agents have task_pickup | ✅ Complete coverage |\n| Classification accuracy | ✅ High confidence routing |\n\n---\n\n### 🔵 Continuous Tasks (Never-Ending)\n\n**Yes, this is possible.** Two approaches:\n\n#### Option A: Session Mode (Built-in)\n```python\nsessions_spawn(\n    task=\"Monitor Parse uptime continuously\",\n    runtime=\"subagent\",\n    mode=\"session\",  # ← Persistent, not one-shot\n    label=\"ogedei-uptime-monitor\"\n)\n```\n- Agent runs indefinitely\n- Can be killed via `subagents action=kill`\n- Best for: monitors, watchers, listeners\n\n#### Option B: Self-Respawning Loop\n```python\n# Agent code\nwhile True:\n    # Do work\n    check_uptime()\n    \n    # Sleep between checks\n    await asyncio.sleep(60)\n    \n    # Optional: re-queue itself\n    if should_continue():\n        queue_next_check()\n```\n- Agent controls its own lifecycle\n- Can update task status in queue\n- Best for: periodic tasks with logic\n\n#### Option C: Heartbeat-Registered Continuous Task\n```python\n# In agent_tasks.py\nhb.register(HeartbeatTask(\n    name=\"uptime_monitor\",\n    agent=\"ogedei\",\n    frequency_minutes=1,\n    max_tokens=100,\n    handler=ogedei_uptime_monitor,\n    continuous=True  # ← Never completes\n))\n```\n- Registered as permanent heartbeat task\n- Runs every N minutes forever\n- Best for: infrastructure monitoring\n\n---\n\n### 📋 Recommended Actions\n\n| Priority | Action | Effort |\n|----------|--------|--------|\n| **P0** | Add task completion feedback loop | Low |\n| **P0** | Add retry logic for failed spawns | Low |\n| **P1** | Reduce spawn-consumer cron to 30s | Low |\n| **P1** | Implement continuous task support (mode=\"session\") | Medium |\n| **P2** | Add Neo4j task history tracking | Medium |\n| **P2** | Add task dependencies/chaining | High |\n\n---\n\n### Want me to implement:\n1. **Task completion feedback** (agent marks done when finished)\n2. **Retry logic** (3x before dead letter)\n3. **Continuous task support** (mode=\"session\" + heartbeat registration)\n4. **Reduce cron latency** (2min → 30s)"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"bailian","model":"qwen3.5-plus","usage":{"input":154492,"output":1782,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":156274,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1772560553760}}
{"type":"message","id":"b2644ee6","parentId":"414c3066","timestamp":"2026-03-03T17:56:16.858Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"## Critical Review: Task Handling & Agent Spawning System\n\n### Current Architecture\n\n```\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│ CHAT FLOW (<10 sec)                                         │\n│ User Message → Kublai → chat_to_task.py → sessions_spawn   │\n└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│ AUTONOMOUS FLOW (~7 min)                                    │\n│ Heartbeat (5min) → task_pickup → spawn-pending.json →      │\n│ spawn-consumer cron (2min) → sessions_spawn                │\n└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n---\n\n### 🔴 Redundancies Found\n\n| # | Issue | Impact | Fix |\n|---|-------|--------|-----|\n| 1 | **spawn-consumer.sh only serves heartbeat** | 2min latency for autonomous tasks | Make heartbeat event-driven or reduce cron to 30s |\n| 2 | **No task completion feedback** | Queue never updated when agent finishes | Agent should mark task complete in queue |\n| 3 | **No failure handling** | Failed spawns lost forever | Add retry logic (3x) + dead letter queue |\n| 4 | **Task status is minimal** | Can't track progress | Add: pending→processing→running→completed/failed |\n| 5 | **No task dependencies** | Can't chain tasks | Add dependency graph (task B waits for task A) |\n\n---\n\n### 🟡 Improvements Needed\n\n| Area | Current | Recommended |\n|------|---------|-------------|\n| **Latency (autonomous)** | ~7 min (5min heartbeat + 2min cron) | <1 min (event-driven heartbeat) |\n| **Task tracking** | JSON file, no history | Neo4j + JSON (queryable history) |\n| **Priority handling** | Basic (high/normal/low) | Priority queue with aging |\n| **Concurrency limits** | None | Max N concurrent per agent |\n| **Task expiration** | None | Auto-expire after 24h |\n\n---\n\n### 🟢 What's Working Well\n\n| Component | Status |\n|-----------|--------|\n| Chat-to-task immediate spawn | ✅ Excellent (<10 sec) |\n| Single queue file | ✅ Simple, debuggable |\n| All 6 agents have task_pickup | ✅ Complete coverage |\n| Classification accuracy | ✅ High confidence routing |\n\n---\n\n### 🔵 Continuous Tasks (Never-Ending)\n\n**Yes, this is possible.** Two approaches:\n\n#### Option A: Session Mode (Built-in)\n```python\nsessions_spawn(\n    task=\"Monitor Parse uptime continuously\",\n    runtime=\"subagent\",\n    mode=\"session\",  # ← Persistent, not one-shot\n    label=\"ogedei-uptime-monitor\"\n)\n```\n- Agent runs indefinitely\n- Can be killed via `subagents action=kill`\n- Best for: monitors, watchers, listeners\n\n#### Option B: Self-Respawning Loop\n```python\n# Agent code\nwhile True:\n    # Do work\n    check_uptime()\n    \n    # Sleep between checks\n    await asyncio.sleep(60)\n    \n    # Optional: re-queue itself\n    if should_continue():\n        queue_next_check()\n```\n- Agent controls its own lifecycle\n- Can update task status in queue\n- Best for: periodic tasks with logic\n\n#### Option C: Heartbeat-Registered Continuous Task\n```python\n# In agent_tasks.py\nhb.register(HeartbeatTask(\n    name=\"uptime_monitor\",\n    agent=\"ogedei\",\n    frequency_minutes=1,\n    max_tokens=100,\n    handler=ogedei_uptime_monitor,\n    continuous=True  # ← Never completes\n))\n```\n- Registered as permanent heartbeat task\n- Runs every N minutes forever\n- Best for: infrastructure monitoring\n\n---\n\n### 📋 Recommended Actions\n\n| Priority | Action | Effort |\n|----------|--------|--------|\n| **P0** | Add task completion feedback loop | Low |\n| **P0** | Add retry logic for failed spawns | Low |\n| **P1** | Reduce spawn-consumer cron to 30s | Low |\n| **P1** | Implement continuous task support (mode=\"session\") | Medium |\n| **P2** | Add Neo4j task history tracking | Medium |\n| **P2** | Add task dependencies/chaining | High |\n\n---\n\n### Want me to implement:\n1. **Task completion feedback** (agent marks done when finished)\n2. **Retry logic** (3x before dead letter)\n3. **Continuous task support** (mode=\"session\" + heartbeat registration)\n4. **Reduce cron latency** (2min → 30s)"}],"api":"openai-responses","provider":"openclaw","model":"delivery-mirror","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1772560576858}}
